Chapter 1
Hello, and thanks for purchasing, Rails for IOS. This book will take
you through the different challenges a beginning programmer may face
when starting to work with APIs alongside the IOS framework. Along the
journey we will cover many different topics, such as installation of Xcode
tool-belt, Ruby on Rails, HomeBrew, Git, and using Heroku. We will also
be covering activeRecord, dependencies (Both Ruby and Objective-C),
good API habits, <<><>><>.
This book is for intermediate level programmers, who are looking
to take their programming to the next level, through database migration
and more. When reading this book, you should have a basic
understanding of and OOP design.
Ruby rst appeared in 1995, around 20 years ago. Ruby was
developed by Yukihiro Mastumoto, who believed python wasnt a
sufcient language for OOP design. So with that in mind he created ruby
with many different features, such as imperative, functional and object
oriented paradigms.
Ruby is an open source platform, so obtaining modules, also known
as gems, is as easy as a simple command line code,

**If you are interested in knowing what each folder that we will use means
continue reading or you can just skip over to the next section.**
App:
This folder contains the following
subfolders ->
Assets: When building web
a p p l i c a t i o n s a n d f r a m e w o r k s ,
a s s e t s a r e t h e
pipeline for CSS and
Javascript that gets worked into
the ERB templates.
Model/View/Controller Folders:
Ruby is built off of a
MVC structure, Model View
Controller.
Created by Travis
Revised by
Rails for IOS Page 10
Essentially when the
client sends a request
to the server ( view to
controller ) the server
looks for a
corresponding model to
update (controller to
model), depending upon
the request. Once the
request is fulfilled or
denied the controller talks back to the view with the
updated model, or error message pertaining to said
request. Everything that is done programmatically
inside of these tutorial will be
Helpers: The Helper folder holds the helper
files for the controllers. Methods that go inside of
these source files are those that need to be kept out
of the way such as defining a method for the project
name. This method is called a bunch in your view but it
looks like it makes the controller file a little more
cluttered. So go ahead and use the helper file!
Bin: The bin folder is primarily for handling
request on the command such as rake request and
database request for the project. The bin folder wont
be used in this tutorial. It should be left alone and
untempered with unless you are a professional
programmer. Tempering with these files could have
unknown side-affects on your project.
Created by Travis
Revised by
Rails for IOS Page 11
Config: The config folder holds 3 important
source files which we will be using:
Database.yml: Inside of this file you will find
the necessary components for
socketing and database control.
Routes.rb: These are the routes for our API
controllers. This file designates what routes are
implemented at any given time. We can use rake
routes at the command line to see what routes are
possible.
Application.rb: When using the server startup
command, this is the file executed in order to run
our application.
Initializer-SubFolder: These files are ran
before the server is uploaded. Some gems have
initializer files necessary in order to use call-
backs for different functions such as mailing
options and picture uploaders.
DB:
The DB folder will hold our schemas for the models.
A Schema is the database tree that is used for our
project.
Created by Travis
Revised by
Rails for IOS Page 12
Public:
The Public folder holds our common routing errors.
For example a 500 error would be equal to the
database or server not responding, a 404 error
would be equal to an unknown page. These error can
be manipulated for your needs. When sending a
response back to the client, we always want to make
sure to use the correct response so that the
fronted can handle it smoother, rather than a bunch
of different errors that could cause confusion.
OtherImportantFiles:
Gemfile:
This file is will hold our dependencies we will use
throughout our project, such as Bcrypt, which as
described before is a gem. When Working with Ruby
unlike python or Node we will be using Gems rather
than modules. So throughout this book you will
probably see me type Gems more than modules.

Inside of sublime-text go to App > Controllers > Application_controller
When starting any API, it is recommended to change with :exception
to :null_session. The reason for this is because when using an API the
state of the server is neither up or down, meaning it is at a RESTful state.
After changing from :exception to :null_session, head over to your cong
folder, and inside of initializers open up inection.rb. A good habit for API
programing is version control.
Version Control - Level: Important
For the rst version of our API we are going to keep the les inside of a
folder named V1 within the API folder. Incase we are going to be making
a V2 or V3 or even a V4 we want to separate our folders nicely without
making a mess. Many developers use this method, and Im sure you will
see it in the future.
So as I began you should be inside Cong > Initializers > Inection.rb.

IOS Framework
Chapter 4
We are half way there! Now we are going to read the data into the
IOS framework.
Hopefully you read the rst chapter and you have Xcode Installed,
go ahead and start a new Xcode project using the OS X command line
template.
Created by Travis
Revised by
Rails for IOS Page 23
Once the project is created, make a new cocoa touch le named
HTTPHelper acting as an NSObject, and place it inside your project
folder.
Now we are going to need to use NSMutableURLRequest, NSData,
and an NSHTTPURLResponse in order to manipulate our data into
readable form over the IOS Framework.
**This book expects that you have some knowledge using Objective-C.
Whenever I create an methods in order to read data / post data via an
API, I always like to have both a POST and a GET method.
Lets go ahead and get started on a creating a GET method inside our IOS
Framework.
Created by Travis
Revised by
Rails for IOS Page 24
Lets break this down, we created a le named HTTPHelper, inside of the
init method, we create the base-url, which for tutorial purposes is
localhost:3000.
Inside the get method we nish our nalURL with the controller we are
passing in and the action we are using. The method part is used for
authorization keys. For example, if you are the admin, your account could
be paired with some sort of key in order to have access to different parts
of the application. Auth-keys will be covered in another part of the
tutorial, for now lets nish reading data via the IOS framework.
We than create an NSURLRequest using the nalURL as [NSURL
URLWithString:NSString]. Than setup the NSURLResponse, followed by
an error.
We than setup the connection using NSData. Once this command is
executed, the data will now hold any data given to us from the endpoint.
Created by Travis
Revised by
Rails for IOS Page 25
This data is usually either JSON or XML encoded into some sort of
programming language unreadable by humans. We must now make the
data readable. So if there was no error, we will continue attempting to
make the data readable using a JSON decoder provided by the IOS
framework.
Now the next part can get a little hard to understand, but when data is
read into the framework Apple tends to create NCSF_Arrays and
NCSF_Dictionaries or even NCSF_Strings, but dont worry these are still
the normal NSString, NSDictionary and NSArray we normally use, they
are just subclasses to the super class. In a later part of this tutorial I will
cover what exact commands allow for the retrieval of either an Array
String or Dictionary, so it will easier to determine what type of object we
are going to want to use for the end Result.
So now we are inside the IF brackets, we must create another error for the
json call, and setup our datatype to return, for now we should be using
NSDictionary, because we will be returning a dictionary with an status
code value and a message, Dont forget to add the following code inside
the header method so other classes know this method exist!
